  "opinion": "As a woman with a master's degree who's been building things with my hands since I was a child, I've seen firsthand how stereotype threat can quietly undermine talent in STEM fields. Growing up in a family where my father had a vocational diploma and my mother a bachelor's degree, I learned early that being 'not the type' to do certain things could be a real barrier. Stereotype threat isn't just about being judged—it's that internalized fear that your own abilities might not measure up when you're in a space where you're expected to conform to a narrow stereotype. In Rome, where I've built my life as a carpenter, I've noticed how this tension plays out in the workplace. For instance, when I'm working with students or colleagues who are also immigrants, I've seen how the pressure to 'prove' they belong in technical fields can lead to self-doubt and even avoidance of challenges. This is especially true for women and people of color who often face implicit biases that don't get acknowledged in the way they're supposed to be. Should we address it? Absolutely. But the way we do it matters—through mentorship, inclusive environments, and creating spaces where people feel safe to make mistakes. I've found that storytelling, like sharing my own journey from the workshop to a master's degree, helps break down these barriers. It's not about fixing people—it's about changing the narrative so that everyone knows they belong. After all, in a city like Rome, where history and innovation coexist, we have the opportunity to build a future where stereotype threat doesn't hold anyone back.",
